\documentclass{article}\begin{document}Reconstructing high-resolution maps of the thermal Sunyaev-Zel'dovich (tSZ) effect, a key tracer of baryonic gas pressure, is hampered by instrumental noise and foreground contamination from sources like the Cosmic Infrared Background (CIB). We present a deep learning framework for super-resolution denoising of tSZ maps from simulated multi-frequency observations mimicking the Simons Observatory. Using hydrodynamical simulations from the FLAMINGO project, we train a two-stage model. First, a U-Net-based Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder (SR-DAE) leverages high-frequency CIB maps as a spatial guide to reconstruct 1-arcmin resolution tSZ maps from lower-resolution inputs, optimized with a composite loss function enforcing both pixel-level accuracy and fidelity to the physical tSZ power spectrum. This deterministic model is then transitioned into a Conditional Diffusion Model (CDM) to generate multiple realizations and provide robust, pixel-level uncertainty quantification. We demonstrate that our approach significantly outperforms standard linear component separation methods, such as constrained Internal Linear Combination and Wiener Filtering, by substantially reducing reconstruction error on the 1--5 arcmin scales critical for studying baryonic feedback. The models prove robust when tested on out-of-distribution scenarios, including the most massive galaxy clusters and high-noise realizations. The final reconstructed maps exhibit a tighter scaling relation between integrated tSZ signal and cluster mass and a power spectrum transfer function near unity across a broad range of angular scales. Furthermore, the uncertainties derived from the CDM are shown to be well-calibrated, providing a reliable measure of reconstruction fidelity.\end{document}

