Current paper introduction: 
The thermal Sunyaev-Zel'dovich (tSZ) effect, the inverse Compton scattering of cosmic microwave background photons by hot, ionized gas, provides a unique window into the distribution of baryonic matter in the universe. As a direct probe of the integrated electron pressure along the line of sight, the tSZ effect is indispensable for studying the thermodynamics of the intracluster and circumgalactic medium, constraining cosmological parameters, and understanding the impact of energetic feedback processes from supernovae and active galactic nuclei. Upcoming surveys, such as the Simons Observatory, are poised to map the microwave sky with unprecedented sensitivity and resolution, promising a wealth of information encoded in the tSZ signal across a wide range of angular scales.

Extracting the faint tSZ signal from these observations, however, presents a formidable challenge. The raw observational maps are a superposition of numerous components, including the primordial cosmic microwave background, instrumental noise, and various astrophysical foregrounds. At the small angular scales crucial for resolving the internal structure of galaxy clusters and filaments---typically on the order of a few arcminutes---the dominant contaminant is the Cosmic Infrared Background (CIB), the integrated emission from dusty, star-forming galaxies. The CIB is not only a significant source of emission but is also spatially correlated with the tSZ signal, as the star formation it traces is intrinsically linked to the feedback mechanisms that heat the surrounding gas. This complex, non-Gaussian relationship makes it exceedingly difficult for traditional linear component separation methods, such as the Internal Linear Combination or Wiener Filtering, to cleanly disentangle the two signals, often leading to biased reconstructions and a loss of small-scale information.

In this paper, we introduce a novel deep learning framework designed to overcome these limitations by reframing the task as a guided super-resolution denoising problem. Instead of treating the CIB as a contaminant to be removed, our approach leverages its spatial information as a conditional guide to reconstruct the underlying tSZ pressure map. We propose a two-stage model that operates on simulated multi-frequency observations tailored to the specifications of the Simons Observatory. The first stage consists of a Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder, which learns to map the noisy, low-resolution input channels to a clean, high-resolution tSZ map. This reconstruction is guided by a composite loss function that enforces both pixel-level accuracy and fidelity to the physical tSZ power spectrum, thereby preventing the generation of unphysical structures.

Recognizing that a single point estimate is insufficient for rigorous scientific analysis, the second stage of our framework transitions this deterministic model into a probabilistic one. We employ a Conditional Diffusion Model, which learns the full conditional probability distribution of the tSZ map given the observational data. By sampling from this distribution, we can not only produce a high-fidelity reconstruction but also generate robust, pixel-level uncertainty maps. We demonstrate that our framework significantly outperforms standard linear methods in recovering the tSZ signal, particularly on the 1--5 arcmin scales most sensitive to baryonic feedback. The resulting maps yield a tighter tSZ signal-mass scaling relation and provide well-calibrated uncertainties, paving the way for more precise cosmological and astrophysical analyses with the next generation of microwave surveys.

